Overview

16/12/2025 Final Project Option 3

Alicia Osorio, Caitlyn Archibald, Samir Jaber, Grace Shin, Ryan Park, Portia Wainwright

Introduction

One of the many unique mysteries of human biology is the ability of a large majority of

cells in the human body to respond to light (Moro et al., 2022). As researchers have worked to

understand why this occurs, one explanation that has gained attention is that all living cells are

also capable of generating light. Biophotons refer to an internally generated stream of extremely

faint, visible-range photons (approximately 100 photons per second) that are emitted by all living

organisms (Benfatto et al., 2023). Unlike bioluminescence, which occurs only in specific species,

biophoton emission is universal across plants, animals, and humans and is many orders of

magnitude weaker. These photons cannot be explained by thermal radiation, as calculations

based on Planck‚Äôs distribution demonstrate that visible-range thermal emission is far too weak to

account for the observed signal. Additionally, biophoton emission ceases entirely at death, ruling

out alternative sources such as radioactive decay or cosmic-ray interactions. Together, these

features highlight the unique nature of biophotons as a non-thermal, life-dependent form of

photon emission.

Studies have shown that biophoton emissions span a broad wavelength range, from

ultraviolet (Œª ‚âà 200 nm) to infrared (Œª ‚âà 950 nm), and exhibit wide variability in intensity (Kam

et al., 2025). It is further believed that mitochondria and microtubules play key roles in

biophoton function. Mitochondria are central to cellular energy production through adenosine

triphosphate (ATP) synthesis, while microtubules are hypothesized to capture and transmit

biophotons during cellular processes.

Based on this understanding, biophoton emission has gained increasing attention for its

potential applications in healthcare and medical diagnostics. Because biophoton activity is

closely linked to cellular metabolism, oxidative stress, and mitochondrial function, changes in

emission patterns can reflect alterations in tissue health and disease state. Research has

demonstrated that inflamed, hypoxic, or infected tissues exhibit measurable differences in optical

properties such as light absorption, scattering, and autofluorescence (Li et al., 2023). The

development of non-invasive medical technologies has been shown to improve patient comfort,

reduce infection risk, enable more frequent monitoring, and lower overall healthcare costs by

minimizing the need for laboratory testing or surgical intervention. As a result, biophoton-based

sensing represents a promising non-invasive diagnostic approach (Baldini et al., 2025).

In particular, wound healing is a dynamic biological process involving inflammation,

angiogenesis, and cellular regeneration, all of which influence biophoton-related optical signals.

Early detection of wound infection remains a significant clinical challenge, as current methods

often rely on visual inspection or laboratory testing that may be subjective, invasive, or delayed.

To address this gap, this project proposes the design of a Biophoton Early Wound Infection

Scanner: a non-contact optical device that utilizes multispectral light and biophotonic principles

---

to detect early physiological changes associated with infection. By identifying subtle optical

signatures linked to inflammation and reduced tissue oxygenation before visible symptoms arise,

this device aims to support faster clinical decision-making, reduce infection-related

complications, and improve patient outcomes.

Hardware Design

The hardware design of the Biophoton Early Wound Infection Scanner focuses on

delivering accurate optical measurements while maintaining a user-friendly and convenient form

factor. Because biophoton emissions occur at extremely low intensities, the device requires

highly sensitive detection components and effective shielding from ambient light (Popp et al.,

1984).

At the core of the system is an ultra-sensitive photonic sensor unit capable of detecting

low-level photon emissions from biological tissue. Photon-counting sensors, such as

single-photon avalanche diodes or compact photomultiplier-based detectors, are well suited for

this application due to their extensive use in experimental studies of ultra-weak photon emission

(Popp et al., 1984; Benfatto et al., 2023). To minimize interference from external light sources,

these detectors are housed within a light-sealed measurement chamber positioned directly above

the wound site.

In addition to passive photon detection, the device employs controlled multispectral

illumination to probe tissue properties known to change during infection and inflammation.

Light-emitting diodes operating at specific wavelengths illuminate the wound surface, allowing

the system to assess optical responses across the visible and near-infrared spectrum. Blue

wavelengths emphasize surface-level changes and bacterial autofluorescence, while green and

red wavelengths interact strongly with hemoglobin and blood volume. Near-infrared light

penetrates deeper into tissue and is commonly used to assess relative oxygenation based on

hemoglobin absorption characteristics (Lu & Fei, 2014; Kam et al., 2025). Optical filters are

incorporated to isolate wavelength-specific signals and enhance measurement accuracy.

The scanner‚Äôs physical housing includes a soft, medical-grade interface that gently seals

against the skin. This seal stabilizes the device during measurements while blocking ambient

light without causing discomfort. Internal sensors verify correct placement prior to data

collection, ensuring consistency between scans. Temperature and humidity sensors are also

integrated to account for environmental conditions that may influence optical measurements or

tissue behavior, particularly during extended monitoring periods (Baldini et al., 2025).

Data collection, timing, and initial signal processing are handled by an onboard

microcontroller. The controller performs basic noise reduction, synchronizes multispectral

illumination with photon detection, and prepares the data for wireless transmission. Processed

---

data are transmitted to a paired smartphone application via Bluetooth Low Energy, a reliable and

low-power communication protocol commonly used in portable medical and health monitoring

devices (Verma et al., 2015).

Power is supplied by a rechargeable lithium-ion battery capable of supporting multiple

scans per charge. Integrated power-management circuitry protects both the battery and optical

components, and charging is achieved through a standard USB connection. Sensitive health

information is not displayed directly on the device; instead, minimal visual indicators provide

feedback on scan progress and connection status. Overall, the hardware design prioritizes

practicality, safety, and sensitivity, enabling non-invasive monitoring of wound-related

physiological changes in both clinical and home settings.

Figure 1: An AI-generated image of the Biophoton Early Wound Infection Scanner

Core Technology and Measurements

Building on the principles of biophoton emission, the core technology of the proposed

system centers on optical measurement of ultra-weak photon signals and wavelength-dependent

tissue responses associated with altered cellular metabolism. Biophoton intensity and temporal

dynamics are closely linked to oxidative biochemical reactions, particularly those involving

---

reactive oxygen species generated during mitochondrial respiration and immune activation.

When tissue becomes stressed, inflamed, or infected, oxidative activity increases, producing

measurable changes in photon emission patterns (Rastogi & Posp√≠≈°il, 2013).

Because biophoton emission occurs at extremely low intensities, detection requires

ultra-sensitive photonic sensors operating under controlled conditions. The scanner therefore

incorporates a light-shielded measurement chamber and photon-counting detectors, such as

single-photon avalanche diodes or photomultiplier-based sensors, which have been widely used

in biophoton research (Popp et al., 1984). These sensors enable reliable measurement of photon

count rates and temporal variability across the visible to near-infrared spectrum.

To complement passive biophoton measurements, the system employs controlled

multispectral illumination to probe tissue features known to change during infection. Shorter

wavelengths reveal surface inflammation and bacterial autofluorescence, while visible and

near-infrared reflectance measurements leverage hemoglobin absorption properties to assess

relative tissue oxygenation (Lu & Fei, 2014). Rather than attempting to diagnose infection

directly, the device evaluates parameters such as emission intensity, wavelength-specific

reflectance ratios, and asymmetries between wounded and adjacent healthy tissue. Together,

these metrics provide a non-contact, physiologically grounded assessment of wound status by

capturing early changes in oxidative metabolism, oxygen availability, and inflammatory activity.

User Experience

The scanner is designed to be intuitive and accessible, allowing users to set up the device,

pair it with a smartphone application, and scan wound sites at home with minimal technical

expertise. Upon unboxing, users receive the handheld scanner, a charging cable, and a QR code

that links directly to the application in the device‚Äôs app store. Once the application is installed,

the scanner connects to the smartphone via Bluetooth wireless technology, which uses

short-range radio waves to enable secure data transmission (Verma et al., 2015).

After pairing, the application prompts the user to answer basic questions about the

wound, including wound type (e.g., scrape, cut, surgical incision), duration, and location on the

body. Users may choose whether to save and track this information over time or to use it solely

for the current scan, ensuring respect for user privacy. Consistent with this privacy-focused

design, the device does not capture photographic images and relies exclusively on optical

scanning.

The application then guides the user through the scanning process. First, the user is

instructed to place the device on nearby healthy skin to generate a personalized baseline

measurement of biophoton activity. After completing the baseline scan, the app prompts the user

---

to remove any bandages, if applicable, and to clean the wound according to medical guidance,

ensuring that the area is clean and dry. The user then places the scanner gently over the wound,

applying light pressure to stabilize the device. The scanner forms a light-blocking seal against

the skin and begins data collection, displaying a progress indicator and prompts such as ‚Äúhold

steady‚Äù if needed. Upon completion, a gentle auditory cue signals that the scan is finished.

Following the scan, the application presents results in clear, non-alarming language. If

healing appears consistent with normal recovery, the app recommends continuing standard

wound care. If early signs of potential infection-related stress are detected, the app advises closer

monitoring and suggests repeating the scan within 12‚Äì24 hours while watching for clinical

symptoms such as increased redness, warmth, or pain. In cases where a high likelihood of

infection is indicated, the app encourages the user to consult a medical professional, framing the

result as increased physiological stress rather than a diagnosis.

Figure 2: An AI-generated image of the application interface after scanning the wound

Business and Marketing

The Biophoton Early Wound Infection Scanner is positioned as a clinical

decision-support and home-monitoring tool rather than a diagnostic medical device. This

positioning is central to both regulatory feasibility and market adoption. By focusing on early

risk detection, trend monitoring, and non-invasive physiological assessment, the device

complements existing wound care practices rather than replacing clinical judgment or laboratory

testing. This approach aligns with broader trends in digital health, which emphasize prevention,

---

monitoring, and patient-centered technologies to reduce clinical burden and improve outcomes

(Baldini et al., 2025).

Primary target markets include hospitals, outpatient wound care clinics, home healthcare

providers, and long-term care facilities. These environments face significant challenges related to

wound infections, particularly among diabetic patients, older adults, post-surgical patients, and

immunocompromised populations. Infected wounds are associated with prolonged healing times,

increased antibiotic use, and higher rates of hospital readmission, creating strong incentives for

early monitoring tools that can detect physiological stress before infection becomes clinically

apparent (Li et al., 2023). In clinical settings, the scanner would serve as a portable adjunct to

routine wound assessment, enabling objective and repeatable monitoring over time.

A secondary market includes at-home wound monitoring for patients recovering from

surgery or managing chronic wounds. In this context, the scanner supports patient engagement

while facilitating communication with healthcare providers through shared data summaries.

Remote monitoring technologies have been shown to improve continuity of care and reduce

unnecessary in-person visits when integrated with mobile health applications (Verma et al.,

2015).

The business model could combine one-time hardware sales with optional

subscription-based software services. Hardware would be sold to healthcare institutions or

individual users, while software subscriptions could offer longitudinal data storage, trend

analysis, clinician dashboards, and electronic health record integration. This hybrid model is

increasingly common in digital health, supporting scalability and continuous system

improvement.

Marketing efforts would emphasize evidence-based validation, safety, and clinical

integration rather than novelty. Adoption depends heavily on clinical trust, requiring

peer-reviewed studies, pilot trials, and transparent performance reporting. All messaging would

avoid diagnostic claims, framing the scanner instead as an early-warning and monitoring tool

that supports informed clinical decision-making.

Ethical Safety and Regulations

The development of the Biophoton Early Wound Infection Scanner raises important

ethical, safety, and regulatory considerations due to its interaction with human health and

sensitive physiological data. From a physical safety perspective, the scanner is inherently low

risk because of its non-invasive, non-contact design. It relies exclusively on low-intensity visible

and near-infrared light, which falls well within established exposure limits for medical optical

---

devices. No ionizing radiation, thermal injury, or tissue penetration is involved, making the

device suitable for repeated use across diverse populations.

Psychological safety is also a key consideration, as health-monitoring technologies can

influence user anxiety and behavior. To mitigate this risk, the scanner avoids diagnostic language

and presents results using graded risk categories that encourage observation or professional

consultation rather than self-treatment.

Managing uncertainty is a central ethical challenge. Wound healing is complex, and

increased inflammation or oxidative activity does not always indicate infection. To prevent

misinterpretation, the system emphasizes longitudinal trends rather than single measurements

and compares wound data against personalized baselines and surrounding healthy tissue.

Rigorous validation through controlled and longitudinal clinical studies is essential to establish

reliability, limitations, and appropriate use. Transparent reporting of accuracy and uncertainty is

critical to maintaining trust.

Data privacy and user autonomy are fundamental ethical priorities. Users retain full

control over data storage and sharing, with options to opt out of storage entirely or selectively

share summaries with healthcare providers. Encryption, anonymization, and secure local

processing protect against unauthorized access. The absence of photographic imaging further

reduces privacy risks and reinforces a privacy-by-design approach.

Regulatory strategy positions the scanner as a non-invasive optical monitoring and

decision-support tool rather than a diagnostic device, aligning with existing regulatory

frameworks used by agencies such as Health Canada and the U.S. Food and Drug

Administration. Approval would require demonstration of electrical and optical safety, software

reliability, cybersecurity protections, and consistent performance across populations and wound

types. Ethical commercialization also demands attention to accessibility and equity, ensuring

affordability, usability, and deployment across diverse care settings.

Ultimately, the ethical responsibility of this technology lies not only in what it measures,

but in how it is framed, validated, regulated, and used. By prioritizing safety, transparency,

privacy, and appropriate regulatory positioning, the Biophoton Early Wound Infection Scanner

can function as a supportive tool that enhances clinical awareness and patient engagement

without overstepping the boundaries of responsible medical innovation.
